#### 2.3.4 Significant figures

* The number of significant figures in a result is simply the number of figures that are known with some degree of reliability.
* Thus, it will be sufficient to give uncertainties to one significant figure (s.f.).
* The measured quantities are then rounded off to the same decimal place (d.p.) as the uncertainties.

Note:

1. All uncertainties are rounded off to 1 significant figure.
2. The derived quantity is then rounded off to the same decimal place as its uncertainty.

Thus, in measuring the length of the glass block, \(L=2.1\pm 0.1\) cm.

\(L=2.10\pm 0.10\) cm is wrong because uncertainty written has 2 significant figure. Uncertainty can only has 1 s.f.

